04162nam a22005295i 9780300147230DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001472307 a10.12987/97803001472302doi  a(DE-B1597)485525  a(OCoLC)1024017891  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aBF103b.R44 1997eb 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a150/.9/0342211 aReed, Edward S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Soul to Mind :bThe Emergence of Psychology, from Erasmus Darwin to William James /cEdward S. Reed. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- t1. In Search of Psychology -- t2. The Impossible Science -- t3. Frankenstein's Science -- t4. The Breakdown in the Concert of European Ideas -- t5. The Brief Life of Natural Metaphysics -- t6. 1848 and All That -- t7. The Three Unconsciousnesses and How They Grew -- t8. The Apotheosis of Positivism -- t9. The Anomalous Mr. Darwin -- t10. The Generation of 1879, or How Philosophy Emerged from Psychology -- t11. William James: Psychology as a Science of Experience -- tBibliographic Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly in the nineteenth century, psychology was considered a science of the soul; by the end of the century, it had abandoned the soul to become a science of the mind, says Edward Reed. In this lively and original account of psychology's formative years, Reed tells the story of the failures and successes of the attempts of nineteenth-century thinkers and practitioners-including philosophers, theologians, medical workers, mesmerists, and even poets-to make psychology into a science. He also situates psychological developments within the social, religious, and literary contexts of the times, taking into account the effects of such significant historical changes as rising nationalism, industrialization, urbanization, and changes in communication.From Soul to Mind introduces a cast that includes not only well-known psychologists and philosophers (Kant, Reid, Darwin, James) but also figures important in their time who are largely forgotten today (R. H. Lotze in Germany, G. H. Lewes in Britain) and literary notables (Mary Shelley, E. T. A. Hoffman, Edgar Allan Poe). Countering the widespread belief that psychology is the offspring of philosophy, Reed contends that modern philosophy arose when academic philosophers sought to distinguish themselves from psychologists. He places the histories of philosophy and psychology within a broad intellectual and social framework and offers a new perspective on the roots of the New Psychology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aPsychologyxHistoryx19th century. 0aPsychologyxHistoryy19th century. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300147230.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles